  "facts": [
    "The English word \"bank\" for a financial institution comes from Old Italian banca “bench,” because medieval money-changers did business on benches; the phrase banca rotta (“broken bench”)—used when a money-changer’s bench was smashed by creditors—is the direct ancestor of the word \"bankrupt.\"",
    "The financial \"bank\" and the river \"bank\" are etymological strangers: the money-related sense is an Italian loanword (attested in English from trade with Lombardy and Venice in the late medieval period), whereas river \"bank\" comes from a Germanic/Old Norse root meaning “ridge,” so their identical spelling is a later coincidence that fuels puns and headlines.",
    "The familiar term \"bank holiday\" literally owes its name to banks: the UK’s Bank Holidays Act of 1871 fixed public holidays on days when banks were closed, so the operational schedule of banks helped shape modern public holiday calendars."
  ]
